    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The genetic determinism argument often relies on studies that attempt to isolate heritability, suggesting that a significant portion of the variance in IQ scores within groups is attributable to genes. Proponents point to twin and adoption studies, which track genetic relatedness to infer how much of the variation is passed down. They argue that these findings demonstrate that inherent, biological predispositions—rather than just the environment—are responsible for the observed average differences between groups.",
